TASK INSTRUCTIONS - PLEASE READ CAREFULLY! The goal of this study is to learn how mind wandering affects how you learn information during reading.

Mind wandering is a term used to describe what occurs when your attention wanders from a task. Sometimes when your mind wanders, you begin thinking about personal events or concerns rather than your task. At other times, your mind can wander because you are bored or tired and you don’t really know what you’re thinking about; all you know is that you are no longer thinking about your task.

Please press the space bar to continue.

In this task, you will read 4 passages and answer reading comprehension questions for each passage.

THE PASSAGES WILL BE PRESENTED IN A SENTENCE-BY-SENTENCE FASHION. PLEASE READ THE SENTENCES AT YOUR NORMAL READING PACE. ONCE YOU HAVE FINISHED READING ONE SENTENCE, PRESS THE SPACE BAR TO MOVE ON TO THE NEXT SENTENCE. Once you've read the sentence you MAY NOT GO BACK.

Please press the space bar to continue.

THE SET OF READING COMPREHENSION QUESTIONS FOR THAT PARTICULAR PASSAGE YOU’VE FINISHED READING WILL APPEAR AFTER EACH PASSAGE, not all together at the end. Like the sentences, once you've answered the questions you MAY NOT GO BACK TO CHANGE YOUR ANSWER.

Please press the space bar to continue.

Additionally, while you are reading you will be randomly interrupted and asked “WERE YOU MIND WANDERING WHEN YOU READ THE PREVIOUS SENTENCE?" You would have to choose either “Yes” or "No" by clicking on the appropriate option.

Please press the space bar to continue.

This entire task is self-paced. Though of course you should try NOT TO go over the task's ending time of 20 minutes. So try to do the task all the way through instead of taking too many small breaks in between. The task isn't long, so you should be able to do it without taking any breaks.

Please press the space bar to continue.
Please press the space bar to start reading the first passage.

Spreadsheet: line_text: Passage 1
Elizabeth Barrett was wise enough to see that Browning was a fine poet.
The young man with the lemon-colored gloves and long dark hair and high-strung, restless manner who had visited her in 1846 had been moved to write to her because she had praised his poetry.

She found the man even more to her liking than the verse, and it was not so very long-only the time between May, 1845 and September, 1846-before Robert Browning had stolen the poetess from the dour father who guarded her like a dragon (never wanting her to marry any man), and taken her with him to Italy and a new life.
One morning, soon after Robert and Elizabeth married; she thrust a manuscript into Robert’s pocket.
Then she ran up to her room, embarrassed by her action.
The manuscript was a sonnet sequence that she had written about their courtship and their love letters.
Mrs. Browning never intended for these poems to be published, but Robert promptly insisted that they must be.
He suggested calling them Sonnets from the Portuguese.
He may have suggested this title to hide the fact that the poems were personal.
He thought that these poems were “the finest sonnets written in our language since Shakespeare’s.”
Robert Browning’s opinion of Sonnets from the Portuguese was flattering to his wife, the same as his opinion of most of her poetry.
He thought that she was a better poet than he was, and the world at that time agreed with him.
He called her his “moon of poets,” and she considered him her sun.
Elizabeth Barrett Browning was a pure singer with a lovely lyrical tenderness.
She was the best poet of her sex since Sappho.
Her Sonnets reveal a woman’s secret soul like no other poetry in our literature up to that time.
They did so with autobiographical honesty, fine moderation and fullness.
Her lyrical mastery shines in many passages of her writings.
Italy was a kind of promised land for Elizabeth Browning.
In the summer, she and her husband lived in Florence or in little villages.
She drank in the sun of the south and the warmth of her husband’s love.
She blossomed in a life of delicate happiness for fifteen years.
She found friends in Italy, most of them cultured Americans.
Hawthorne saw the Browning's there: the New England thinker and essayist Margaret Fuller visited them.
The painter Story and the young sculptress Harriet Hosmer came.
One caller records that Robert Browning was “simple, natural, and playful,” and that Mrs. Browning was all “genius and sensibility.”
Daytimes Browning walked forth with Elizabeth's little dog Flush, but he seldom could be lured from his home evenings.
One privileged intruder, coming frequently at night to join the poets over hot chestnuts and mulled wine, found talk good and laughter plentiful.
He found the talk good and the laughter plentiful.
The Brownings had a son, Robert Weidemann Browning, during the third year of their stay in Italy.
But a strain of dark dread began to creep through this happy life.
Elizabeth Browning’s father died still disapproving of her marriage.
He had refused to see her or to allow any of his family to see her.
Elizabeth’s dearly loved sister died and left three children who were all younger than her own boy.
Elizabeth drooped and grieved a little and Robert shielded her from ordinary visitors.
She had a sudden and alarming attack of sickness but was not considered in any danger.
One night, soon after, she awoke from a troubled sleep, apparently with no idea that she was about to leave Robert.
She spoke tenderly about her love for him. In his arms, her head drooped as though in a faint, but it was the end.
Profound and lasting was Browning's grief. “Looking back,” he said, “I see that we have been all the time walking over a torrent on a straw.”

Spreadsheet: line_text: Passage 2
The nucleus of an atom is held together by a kind of energy called atomic energy.
The sun’s energy comes from atomic reactions.
These reactions occur when the nuclei of hydrogen build up the nuclei of helium.
An atomic nucleus is made of particles, but the mass of the atomic nucleus is less than the total mass of the particles.
The reason for this is that part of the mass of particles is changed into energy when a nucleus is formed.
This energy then radiates away.
The quantity of energy released in reactions of this kind is almost inconceivably greater than the quantity released by any other type of reaction involving similar quantities of material.
Every second, the sun sends a million times more energy into space than we have stored in all of our coal, petroleum, and natural gas fields.
We could revolutionize the world if we could duplicate the method that releases such energy.
This possibility is not a fantasy, just as it was not a fantasy to imagine developing an atom bomb in 1900.
The time may come when the hydrogen from a cubic mile of sea water will provide enough energy to satisfy our needs at the 1960 rate for 300 centuries.

The quantity of energy released in an atomic reaction is spoken of as how much greater than with other types of reactions?

Spreadsheet: response_d: what happens in an atomic reaction

Spreadsheet: line_text: Passage 3
Fungi give cheese the flavor, odor, and character that gourmets so highly prize.
One of the first molds was found in caves near the French village of Roquefort.
According to legend, a peasant boy left his lunch, which was a mild fresh piece of goat cheese, in one of the caves.
When he returned, he found the cheese marbled, tart, and fragrant.
Only cheeses that come from the area around these particular caves are allowed to bear the name of Roquefort.
As early as the seventeenth century, ergot, the fungus of rye, was used to facilitate childbirth.
It causes the contraction of involuntary muscles, particularly in the uterus.
In the twentieth century, ergot has once more attracted interest as the source of the chemical from which the hallucinogenic drug LSD is derived.
Most modern antibiotics are produced by fungi.
Alexander Fleming discovered the first of these antibiotics.
A mold of the genus Penicillium had contaminated a culture of staphylococcus bacteria that was growing on a nutrient agar plate.
Alexander noted that the mold completely halted the growth of the bacteria.
Antibiotics, of which many hundreds have now been discovered, are substances produced by a living organism that injure another living organism.
All of these are substances produced by one living organism that injures another living organism.

How many antibiotics have been discovered?

Spreadsheet: line_text: Passage 4
Once in a while you will hear about an artist who was recognized as a master during his lifetime, but was then almost forgotten after his death.
A good example is the painter, Domenicos Theotocopoulos.
He was known as El Greco because of his Greek ancestry.
After pursuing his early career in Italy, El Greco settled in the Spanish city of Toledo, where he prospered for the rest of his life.
He prospered there for the rest of his life.
History forgot El Greco for nearly three hundred years.
Then, artists and critics of the twentieth century rediscovered him.
The power of El Greco’s intensely emotional style can be felt most strongly in his later paintings, such as the famous View of Toledo.
He painted this canvas in 1610, only a few years before his death.
It is a strange landscape.
One notices that eerie, silvery buildings take on a ghostlike stillness next to the explosive light of the sky and the writhing forms of the countryside below.
Curiously, about the same time, another important artist was scorned even by many of his contemporaries.
This artist was Caravaggio.
He was a self-taught painter who came to Rome around 1590 from a small town in Lombardy.
Caravaggio’s critics complained that he treated sacred religious subjects in a low, vulgar way by including the faces and figures of common people in his paintings.
By using stark contrasts of light and shadow, Caravaggio managed to conjure up unforgettable scenes of dramatic realism.

Elizabeth Barrett was wise enough to see that Browning was a fine poet.
The young man with the lemon-colored gloves and long dark hair and high-strung, restless manner who had visited her in 1846 had been moved to write to her because she had praised his poetry.

She found the man even more to her liking than the verse, and it was not so very long-only the time between May, 1845 and September, 1846-before Robert Browning had stolen the poetess from the dour father who guarded her like a dragon (never wanting her to marry any man), and taken her with him to Italy and a new life.
One morning, soon after Robert and Elizabeth married; she thrust a manuscript into Robert’s pocket.
Then she ran up to her room, embarrassed by her action.
The manuscript was a sonnet sequence that she had written about their courtship and their love letters.
Mrs. Browning never intended for these poems to be published, but Robert promptly insisted that they must be.
He suggested calling them Sonnets from the Portuguese.
He may have suggested this title to hide the fact that the poems were personal.
He thought that these poems were “the finest sonnets written in our language since Shakespeare’s.”

He thought that she was a better poet than he was, and the world at that time agreed with him.

In the summer, she and her husband lived in Florence or in little villages.

Spreadsheet: line_text: Passage 2
The nucleus of an atom is held together by a kind of energy called atomic energy.
The sun’s energy comes from atomic reactions.
These reactions occur when the nuclei of hydrogen build up the nuclei of helium.
An atomic nucleus is made of particles, but the mass of the atomic nucleus is less than the total mass of the particles.
The reason for this is that part of the mass of particles is changed into energy when a nucleus is formed.
This energy then radiates away.
The quantity of energy released in reactions of this kind is almost inconceivably greater than the quantity released by any other type of reaction involving similar quantities of material.
Every second, the sun sends a million times more energy into space than we have stored in all of our coal, petroleum, and natural gas fields.
We could revolutionize the world if we could duplicate the method that releases such energy.
This possibility is not a fantasy, just as it was not a fantasy to imagine developing an atom bomb in 1900.
The time may come when the hydrogen from a cubic mile of sea water will provide enough energy to satisfy our needs at the 1960 rate for 300 centuries.

Spreadsheet: line_text: Passage 3
Fungi give cheese the flavor, odor, and character that gourmets so highly prize.
One of the first molds was found in caves near the French village of Roquefort.
According to legend, a peasant boy left his lunch, which was a mild fresh piece of goat cheese, in one of the caves.
When he returned, he found the cheese marbled, tart, and fragrant.
Only cheeses that come from the area around these particular caves are allowed to bear the name of Roquefort.
As early as the seventeenth century, ergot, the fungus of rye, was used to facilitate childbirth.
It causes the contraction of involuntary muscles, particularly in the uterus.
In the twentieth century, ergot has once more attracted interest as the source of the chemical from which the hallucinogenic drug LSD is derived.
Most modern antibiotics are produced by fungi.
Alexander Fleming discovered the first of these antibiotics.
A mold of the genus Penicillium had contaminated a culture of staphylococcus bacteria that was growing on a nutrient agar plate.
Alexander noted that the mold completely halted the growth of the bacteria.
Antibiotics, of which many hundreds have now been discovered, are substances produced by a living organism that injure another living organism.
All of these are substances produced by one living organism that injures another living organism.

Spreadsheet: line_text: Passage 2
The nucleus of an atom is held together by a kind of energy called atomic energy.
The sun’s energy comes from atomic reactions.
These reactions occur when the nuclei of hydrogen build up the nuclei of helium.
An atomic nucleus is made of particles, but the mass of the atomic nucleus is less than the total mass of the particles.
The reason for this is that part of the mass of particles is changed into energy when a nucleus is formed.
This energy then radiates away.
The quantity of energy released in reactions of this kind is almost inconceivably greater than the quantity released by any other type of reaction involving similar quantities of material.
Every second, the sun sends a million times more energy into space than we have stored in all of our coal, petroleum, and natural gas fields.
We could revolutionize the world if we could duplicate the method that releases such energy.
This possibility is not a fantasy, just as it was not a fantasy to imagine developing an atom bomb in 1900.
The time may come when the hydrogen from a cubic mile of sea water will provide enough energy to satisfy our needs at the 1960 rate for 300 centuries.

Fungi give cheese the flavor, odor, and character that gourmets so highly prize.
One of the first molds was found in caves near the French village of Roquefort.

When he returned, he found the cheese marbled, tart, and fragrant.
Only cheeses that come from the area around these particular caves are allowed to bear the name of Roquefort.
As early as the seventeenth century, ergot, the fungus of rye, was used to facilitate childbirth.
It causes the contraction of involuntary muscles, particularly in the uterus.
In the twentieth century, ergot has once more attracted interest as the source of the chemical from which the hallucinogenic drug LSD is derived.
Most modern antibiotics are produced by fungi.
Alexander Fleming discovered the first of these antibiotics.
A mold of the genus Penicillium had contaminated a culture of staphylococcus bacteria that was growing on a nutrient agar plate.
Alexander noted that the mold completely halted the growth of the bacteria.
Antibiotics, of which many hundreds have now been discovered, are substances produced by a living organism that injure another living organism.
All of these are substances produced by one living organism that injures another living organism.

Spreadsheet: line_text: Passage 2
The nucleus of an atom is held together by a kind of energy called atomic energy.
The sun’s energy comes from atomic reactions.
These reactions occur when the nuclei of hydrogen build up the nuclei of helium.
An atomic nucleus is made of particles, but the mass of the atomic nucleus is less than the total mass of the particles.
The reason for this is that part of the mass of particles is changed into energy when a nucleus is formed.
This energy then radiates away.
The quantity of energy released in reactions of this kind is almost inconceivably greater than the quantity released by any other type of reaction involving similar quantities of material.
Every second, the sun sends a million times more energy into space than we have stored in all of our coal, petroleum, and natural gas fields.
We could revolutionize the world if we could duplicate the method that releases such energy.
This possibility is not a fantasy, just as it was not a fantasy to imagine developing an atom bomb in 1900.
The time may come when the hydrogen from a cubic mile of sea water will provide enough energy to satisfy our needs at the 1960 rate for 300 centuries.

Fungi give cheese the flavor, odor, and character that gourmets so highly prize.
One of the first molds was found in caves near the French village of Roquefort.
According to legend, a peasant boy left his lunch, which was a mild fresh piece of goat cheese, in one of the caves.
When he returned, he found the cheese marbled, tart, and fragrant.
Only cheeses that come from the area around these particular caves are allowed to bear the name of Roquefort.
As early as the seventeenth century, ergot, the fungus of rye, was used to facilitate childbirth.
It causes the contraction of involuntary muscles, particularly in the uterus.
In the twentieth century, ergot has once more attracted interest as the source of the chemical from which the hallucinogenic drug LSD is derived.
Most modern antibiotics are produced by fungi.
Alexander Fleming discovered the first of these antibiotics.
A mold of the genus Penicillium had contaminated a culture of staphylococcus bacteria that was growing on a nutrient agar plate.
Alexander noted that the mold completely halted the growth of the bacteria.
Antibiotics, of which many hundreds have now been discovered, are substances produced by a living organism that injure another living organism.
All of these are substances produced by one living organism that injures another living organism.

The power of El Greco’s intensely emotional style can be felt most strongly in his later paintings, such as the famous View of Toledo.
He painted this canvas in 1610, only a few years before his death.
It is a strange landscape.
One notices that eerie, silvery buildings take on a ghostlike stillness next to the explosive light of the sky and the writhing forms of the countryside below.
Curiously, about the same time, another important artist was scorned even by many of his contemporaries.
This artist was Caravaggio.
He was a self-taught painter who came to Rome around 1590 from a small town in Lombardy.
Caravaggio’s critics complained that he treated sacred religious subjects in a low, vulgar way by including the faces and figures of common people in his paintings.
By using stark contrasts of light and shadow, Caravaggio managed to conjure up unforgettable scenes of dramatic realism.
